    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": "How long does the scan take?",
        "answer": "30–60 minutes, depending on the sequences required.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Is contrast injection always required?",
        "answer": "No. It’s used only when tumour or vascular detail is needed.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Can children undergo this protocol?",
        "answer": "Yes. Paediatric coils and sedation options are available.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "What if I am claustrophobic?",
        "answer": "We offer an open-bore 70 cm scanner and mild sedation on request.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "When will reports be ready?",
        "answer": "Within 24 hours; urgent cases within 2 hours.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "When will my surgeon use these images?  ",
        "answer": "The images and data from your **MRI Brain Navigation Protocol** are processed shortly after your scan is completed. Your neurosurgeon will then use this detailed 3D map to meticulously plan the surgical approach. During the actual operation, these images are loaded into a neuronavigation system, which your surgeon uses in real-time to guide their instruments, effectively providing a \"GPS for the brain.\" This is **how neuronavigation MRI guides surgery** to achieve optimal results."
      }
    ],
